segments.text: After that had gone on for about two or three months, I knew that something was basically wrong and I wasn't happy.
A man's not happy that he's working, you better look at it.
So I went in to see my superior, Mr. Cottingham, the sailor manager, and he took me in to Lamar Fleming, who was the
Top man with Addison Clayton.
Will Clayton at that time was appointed Secretary of State by the President Roosevelt.
But Lamar Fleming listened to me and he said, Dick, you'll always have a job with Addison Clayton.
But circumstances being what they are, I'd get out of the cotton butters too.
And I did.
Did you, in 1937, did you and your classmates anticipate World War II?
As I said, when I went there, went to Europe, and I saw what was going on in Germany, Luther Jones, Bailey Conner and I and all of us were very upset, very concerned about it.
Let's see, other campus traditions, silver taps, was it held and if so where and what did it mean?
Held then just about the way it's held today.
Had a military walk there, back of the YMCA, right in front of Old Main and it was a very significant occasion.
Nothing more beautiful in the world.
When you hear that silver taps at night and you think about the individual, we usually knew all our old classmates and those things that happened.
We didn't have many though, fortunately.
One or two were killed in accidents and so forth.
Did anybody ever act silly?
Was the behavior of everyone appropriate?
Did they take silver taps seriously?
Oh, absolutely.
No one would have thought of doing anything that would mar the ceremony that they would be grabbed physically and taken out and handled proper way.
Was muster held then?
Must have was held then, but it was not as significant as it is today.
Do you remember where?
Well, frankly, I don't.
It was held, I think, on the drill field.
I'm not sure.
I don't know.
What about Bonfire?
We always had the bonfire but there again I didn't take part in it actually because of my job.
Where was it held?
Where'd they burn it?
Right there on the drill field.
And what was in it?
just wherever we could find stuff that would burn, you know, trees.
Was there any kind of structure that was quite often at the top of the bonfire?
I wasn't that close to it, really, to know just how it was put together and whether it was done by, mainly by students or by who was hired to do it or got it done.
I think it was the students mainly.
I wanted to pour it actually into that.
Let's see.
Now these may not relate to your date.
Hollywood, Uncle Ed's, Running Wood and Water.
Did those?
All of them were familiar.
And I had friends I know who participated, but I didn't.
What was Hollywood?
I don't.
I just don't remember the name of it.
I presume it was a little nightclub where people could go and put a quarter in a nickel machine and dance and drink a little beer on the side of something.
Was Uncle Ed's?
Uncle Ed's Seminole.
As I recall in my recollection, what others said about it.
I don't know.
All right.
Explain Aggie spirit.
What is Aggie spirit?
Well, the Aggie spirit is indefinable, as Buckwaters would say, pretty well.
Except if you're an Aggie, you know what it is.
I think I mentioned to you a little earlier that the Aggie spirit probably identifies me with true grit.
It identifies with the A&M man, the Charles and
the great things that happened to him throughout his career at A&M.
Each man had his own separate memories.
Mine revolve around the individuals that I love there, like Frank Anderson, like Finn Penworthy, like Buddy Morgan, like T.O.
Walden, like Hank Ashford,
He never, McQuillan, Mike McQuillan, there was no greater A&M man than Mike McQuillan and what he did for A&M has never been properly identified and a book ought to be written about Mike.
He was a Scotchman, he was a class of 21, he was dedicated to building a former student association and later
stepped down to take over and be the first president of the Development Foundation because he saw how great the Development Foundation might be and what it would mean to A&M.
So he took down to take over that leadership and put it on the map.
And I never knew anyone who was more dedicated to A&M than Mike.
as our first, not our first, but our second or third association secretary.
Of course, Ike Ashman, one of our first, if not the first, of the official association.
I know there were student organizations before that, and we had several presidents.
Those I didn't know, but starting with Ike Ashman on the back, I knew practically all of them.
and know that fine contribution.
So what did it mean to you, what has it meant to your life that you attended A&M?
Well, A&M has very special, very special benefits to any young man.
Number one, it offers

two careers that offers whatever you want to specialize in and you've got a wide variety from agriculture to petroleum to medicine to you name it to aspire to a degree which you also back in old days special and you still have it throughout Corps cadets an opportunity to get a commission in the armed services.
To me back in old days
not only helped me get through A&M because it paid me a little money, but it also gave me leadership training that I might not have gotten anywhere else.
I was fortunate enough to get into the lead cavalry service where I learned to love horses, learned to ride well, and learned to admire the service and what it stood for.
And it served me well as I went when World War I came around.
Instead of going in as an enlisted man and going through all that tomfoolery, I immediately stepped in as an officer and was called to active duty with the Air Force.
And I went from one very important assignment to another, commandant cadets, director and executive officer of a base.

Wangella Staff School, the Air Staff School, Overseas, Executive Officer of the 38th Bomb Group, and I moved from Lengarian Gulf to Okinawa and had fantastic memories and opportunities and dangers that I came through.
But that's just one thing.
Of course, your friends you make there,
I think stay with you with life.
This coming October, here in Corpus Christi, a class of 37, of which I was a member, will meet for its, what year will that be?
61 years.
Anniversary meeting.
and we'll have quite a turnout.
But we're working right now.
I've got a list upstairs.
I've got through Connie at the Association of Former Students Office with labels to all present living members of the class of 37.
They'll all get a special letter from our committee down here for Aggies from the class of 37.
In addition to that, we'll call
Each one of us, every one of them that we know, and we're going to have quite a three-day party and an interesting time.
So fellowship and the romance of the Aggie ring should never be to any young student who's contemplating whether or not to go to A&M or try to go to A&M.
That ring has meant more to me in my business life
and my social life, and my friendships, and most anything that, you know, I don't believe in wearing jewelry.
I wouldn't advise any woman to wear a big diamond ring or a Rolex watch or anything, but I just had one of my best friends slap down in her garage, you may have read about it in Houston,
She was the 78th woman who'd done that and the jewelry was stolen from her and she was kicked in the face and brutally treated.
But this ring, just like one of the most interesting instances, was during the war.
I was moving my 38th Bomb Group from Lingerie and Guff.
I had orders to move it to Okinawa and
Okinawa, we were to move and operate off of Yontan Strip, the biggest, busiest airstrip in the world at the time.
So I went with my orders and took a sergeant with me and went up as a forward echelon to find a bivouac area, a new bivouac area, and prepare for the move.
And I got up there, I went into Bomber Command and find a buddy major there who took me in
and he said, well, here's a map of the island, Colonel Connolly, and let's see where the 38th Bomb Group's going to be.
He said, hey, I'm down the strip, right at the end of the strip.
Well, yeah, yeah, you are.
You're very convenient to the field.
It's the perfect spot for you.
I said, Major, who made that decision?
He said, I'm not about to put my troops at the end of that runway.
They know planes are jettisoned and don't
Bombs jettison sometimes, and sometimes they don't make it off the end of that runaway.
They just make it off the end of the runaway.
I said, I'm going to put my troops there.
He said, sir, this is a tight situation.
We've got lots of coming in here.
He said, I can't change that.
I said, well, who makes that decision?
He said, well, you'll have to see Colonel Delbert Ward, sir.
I said, well, where's Colonel Delbert Ward?
He said, well, he's a bomber commandant, Air Force commandant.
Fifth Air Force Commander, well, you take me to him.
He said, well, I'll be glad to get you over there.
So he ran with me.
He kept me over there.
Fortunately, I caught Delvin Ward in at his tent there.
Walked in, introduced myself to him.
First thing I saw was his A&M ring.
First thing he saw was my A&M ring.
Well, sit down, Dick.
So we talked about A&M.
We had coffee together.
We were friends immediately and
He said, what's your problem?
What can I do for you?
And I told him.
He looked at it.
He said, my God, we did make a mistake, didn't we?
He said, come with me.
Put me in his Jeep.
We rode around the island.
He found me a spot, a high spot on the island about 10 minutes from the strip where we had a great breeze overlooking the China Sea.
I had the best spot on the island.
I couldn't accomplish it without his help.
He wouldn't have done that for just anybody.
He was too busy.
I've got a book by the other ward I want you to read.
I'll give it to you.
All right.
The last question that I have scheduled is a very serious one.
What feelings do you hold in your heart now for Texas A&M?
Well, I spend a good part of my time each year working for A&M.
And I say working for A&M, directly or indirectly.

Because of my long association with A&M through the former student association, through Corpus Christi A&M Club, through many other areas that I've worked in, I have called some mommas and dads and students.
They want to get this child in A&M.
What can I do?
Well, I can only encourage them.
I can only, what I do in every case, I'll just give you one example that occurred this year that I'm very proud of.
It was a young Hispanic who came to me, and he happened to be the daughter of a nurse who had taken care of my wife when she had cancer.
Wonderful, wonderful woman.
And this was her only son.
She did have two daughters who'd gone on and done well in college.
And he had gotten to high school.
He was a gang member his first two years.
And had done extremely poorly, although he had, in math, he'd done extremely well.
He had a very good mind.
And I checked up on him.

But he came to see me, and he wrote a letter, told me that he'd met a gang member, but he'd fought his way out of that because of the pressure his mother and his sisters and friends had put on him, and he'd seen the light.
And he had, thank God, he said, it wasn't with pistols, I did it with my fist.
And he said, I want to go to A&M.
I'm interested in math, and I know I can excel if I have the opportunity, but I know because of my first two years
were poor, I'm going to have a hard time getting in.
But his junior and his senior year, he did excel.
We talked to his math teacher.
His math teacher said, this young man has unusual ability.
He can be a great mathematician.
And we need to somehow get him in there.
I got ahold of Jim Reynolds and Pam.
And somehow, he made it.
And he's doing extremely well.
He's in the Corps.
But the main thing is he's a role model now that we can use in these high schools.
Oh, yes.
And it's great.
Have I left anything out that you particularly wanted to share?
Well, there's several things that I might talk about.
In fact, I got a whole bunch of stuff I pulled out of a fire here that we go through, but one thing we mentioned was the cotton ball.
They no longer have a cotton ball.
And cotton sort of became the way it was.
King cotton in Texas is no longer king cotton, but more and more, they're planting more and more cotton.
But that occasion of the cotton ball was a great event on the campus.
And I hated to see it disappear.
And I wrote to her about it at the time.
And that's one thing I might mention.
The other thing, I noticed that you've done some work in your career with the Danforth Foundation.
I was one of the fortunate ones who was a Danforth Summer Fellowship winner with a man named Horn, Jeff Horn, in my class.
two of us were selected because they couldn't make a decision between us.
And so they asked permission from Danforth for two to go represent A&M.
That's some of them.
That was a fantastic experience.
I don't know that they're still doing that or not.
I don't think so.
But somehow, someone ought to get with the, you know, that recently Danforth was sold and bought by another company.
Well, and the Danforth Foundation gave all of its money to Washington University St. Louis.
Darn it.
Because they were doing great work with those summer programs.
Oh, I'll tell you.
They took a group of outstanding young men from the land grant colleges across the nation.
They took us into St. Louis, and we worked for six weeks, if I recall correctly, or maybe it was two weeks in St. Louis.
But we worked two or three days in the sales department, two or three days in the research department, two or three days in the accounting department, and so forth.
we got a background of what a business is.
And then Mr. Danforth himself was the founder of the American Youth Foundation camp at Shelton, Michigan.
Been there.
And we were there for at least a month.
And he brought in every week or twice a week some outstanding individuals in the business
religious or government, political world, and with us, who chowed with us, who swam with us, who talked to us over the bonfire every night.
And Mr. Danforth himself led that.
And it was one of the great experiences of my life
And no company could do anything greater than to continue that.
If Danforth can no longer do it, we, you and I, should find some company to do something similar.
Oh, I agree.
Because it would build the leaders in that group.
I still have touch with some of them.
One of them,
is in Hamburg, Louisiana.
His name is Lucian Laborde.
He was recently given an honorary degree by LSU.
And we still stay in touch.
He's one of the great men of the South.
And his brother's the same way.
But others I know have done equally well.
And we can give great credit to William A. Stanton for them.
That is one thing I might mention.
I've talked about Penny and what our intramural program meant to us back in those days.
I don't know why this can't be expanded more than maybe it's being done.
I'm not familiar what's being done, but if we had the kind of leader Penny did, he made it interesting.
He made it something we wanted to do.
There's so many activities we can get into and it's also leadership training.

But what I'd like to see more done and more attention given is to what is being done through the Memorial Student Center with our many programs, student programs that Jim Reynolds-Hedge is doing such a fantastic job with Jane Bailey and his group.

I don't know whether around 750 different student programs if I recall correctly last I heard involving many thousands of students in different activities each one of them may be a different thing maybe it's stamp collecting maybe it's it could be anything or whatever their interests are they can follow it

and have some student leadership and back up through Jim's staff to help them raise money, whatever they need, and organize and do something useful and something worthwhile that they'll always treasure.
And this sort of leadership training, to me, today must take place
That's within a mural of leadership and training.
After all, we're limited now in our corps.
Our corps is doing a fantastic job.
And no one could say more things about the corps than I do.
I treasure it.
But Earl Rudder was right indefinitely.
There was no way our institution could continue to grow as long as we had a limited 2,000 contracts.
And there was hell of that whether you were 40,000 students or 6,000 students.
And it was unfair to the student body to get them in and make them take two years of hard training as a freshman and sophomore in Bull Tech and then not offer them the
a reward of being able at least to hopefully get a contract with the government.

That limited the odds so much that it was taken away from my enrollment and hurting A&M badly and this was changed and it was changed in such a way that it still kept our core in an elite process and it is an elite organization.
One that we can all take tremendous pride in and want to preserve and want to honor and want to continue to keep on the top shelf of A&M.
